  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. These frameworks create obligations for signatory nations to criminalize money laundering, establish regulatory frameworks, and cooperate internationally. Here are some of the most important ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate internationally to combat it.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expands the scope of anti-money laundering efforts beyond drug trafficking to cover a wider range of serious crimes. It also emphasizes international cooperation in investigation, prosecution, and asset recovery.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses on combating corruption, including the laundering of proceeds derived from corrupt practices.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or convention, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist financing. These recommendations provide a comprehensive framework of measures that countries should implement to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. The FATF monitors countries' compliance with these recommendations.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):** This convention promotes common criminal justice policies in Europe with the aim of depriving criminals of the proceeds of their illegal activities.\n\n*   **European Union Directives:** The European Union has issued several directives on money laundering, which set minimum standards for member states and aim to harmonize anti-money laundering regulations across the EU.\n\nThese international laws and standards have significantly shaped national legislation around the world, leading to the criminalization of money laundering in most countries and the establishment of regulatory frameworks to prevent and detect it.\n\nIt's important to note that the effectiveness of these laws depends on their implementation and enforcement by individual countries, as well as the level of international cooperation.",
